# .NET testing (Jurupema)

## Determinism

Tests must produce the same outcome on every run. Do not rely on unbounded randomness or wall-clock time without control.

- Prefer a **fixed seed** for Bogus (e.g. `new Faker { Random = new Randomizer(12345) }` or a `const int` on the test class).
- Avoid asserting on `DateTime.UtcNow` unless the clock is faked or the value is injected.
- When random IDs are needed, derive them from the seeded faker or explicit constants—not `new Random()` per run without a seed.

## Arrange, Act, Assert

Structure each test with explicit phases and comments:

```csharp
// Arrange
// ...

// Act
// ...

// Assert
// ...
```

Keep **Act** to a single logical behavior (one call or one `act` delegate for exception tests).

## Multiple assertions

When asserting more than one outcome in the same test, wrap checks in **`Assert.Multiple`** (xUnit v3) so all failures surface in one run:

```csharp
Assert.Multiple(
    () => Assert.Equal(expectedA, actualA),
    () => Assert.Equal(expectedB, actualB));
```

Use a single assertion when there is only one check.

## Builders

Encapsulate test data construction in **builder classes** under `tests/**/Builders/` (or the project’s agreed test folder). Tests should not duplicate long object initialization or Bogus field rules in every method.

- Builders accept an optional **`Faker`** (or use a seeded instance) so the same seed flows through related entities in one test.
- Expose fluent `With…` methods for the fields tests need to override; sensible defaults live in `Build()`.
